      "content": "You probably mean LangGraph (capitalization corrected). In short: LangGraph is a low-level orchestration framework and runtime for building, managing, and deploying long-running, stateful agents and workflows. It focuses on agent orchestration (not prompt abstractions) so you can build reliable, durable, inspectable agent systems.\n\nKey points\n- Purpose: Orchestrate long-running, stateful agents and workflows (durable execution, retries, state persistence).\n- Main capabilities: durable execution (resume after failures), streaming, human-in-the-loop interrupts, comprehensive memory, observability/tracing (with LangSmith), and production-ready deployment.\n- API shapes: Provides both a Graph API (node/edge style orchestration) and a Functional API (callable workflows) so you can choose the abstraction that fits your design.\n- Integrations: Works standalone but integrates with LangChain components and the LangChain ecosystem (Python and JS/TS SDKs available).\n- Typical use cases: complex multi-step agents, long-running automations, RAG/SQL agents, human-in-the-loop workflows, and systems that require debugging/traceability.\n\nQuick install and tiny example (Python)\n- Install: pip install -U langgraph\n- Minimal example (conceptual):\n  from langgraph.graph import StateGraph, MessagesState, START, END\n  def mock_llm(state): return {\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"ai\",\"content\":\"hello world\"}]}\n  graph = StateGraph(MessagesState); graph.add_node(mock_llm); graph.add_edge(START,\"mock_llm\"); graph.add_edge(\"mock_llm\",END)\n  graph = graph.compile(); graph.invoke({\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"hi!\"}]})\n\nWhere to read more\n- Official docs: https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langgraph/overview.md (there are detailed guides, quickstarts, and reference docs for both Python and JS/TS SDKs)\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- Walk through a quickstart tutorial and build a 
simple agent with you\n- Explain differences between the Graph vs Functional APIs and when to use each\n- Show a more complete code example (Python or JS) for a specific use case you have in mind—what would you like next?",
